As I see in your function you are assigning `array` to `array`. Arrays are `objects` in JS and behaves not as `primitives`. After that assignment both arrays would change if any changes would be made in any of them.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let arr1 = [1, 2, 3];
    let arr2 = [4, 5, 6];

    arr1 = arr2;

    arr2[2] = 999;

    console.log(arr1[2]); // Will also log 999

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

If you want to copy values but not reference to the array you can use `Array.from()` method:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let arr1 = [1, 2, 3];
    let arr2 = [4, 5, 6];

    arr1 = Array.from(arr2);

    arr2[2] = 999;

    console.log(arr1[2]); // Will log 6

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

