```

[Playground][1] (with multiple const implementations)


  [1]: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2018&amp;gist=a53d3f0f9c8ee12f96618a8510ba4b4f

You can get rid of the compiler warning by declaring `template` to have type [`PhantomData::&lt;X&gt;`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/std/marker/struct.PhantomData.html):

```
use std::marker::PhantomData;

trait U32Const {
    const VAL: u32;
}

struct U32Const10;
impl U32Const for U32Const10 {
    const VAL: u32 = 10;
}

struct MyType&lt;X: U32Const&gt; {
    val: u32,
    template: PhantomData::&lt;X&gt;,
}

impl&lt;X: U32Const&gt; MyType&lt;X&gt; {
    fn do_something(&amp;self) -&gt; u32 {
        self.val * X::VAL
    }
}

fn main() {
    let a = MyType::&lt;U32Const10&gt; {
        val: 20,
        template: PhantomData,
    };
    println!(&quot;{}&quot;, a.do_something());
}
```
[playground](https://play.integer32.com/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2018&amp;gist=e6d8a717b1798accd861abbeaa223a51)

You still need to initialize it, but it doesn&#39;t use any memory and the compiler won&#39;t complain when you don&#39;t use it.

